$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-001

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q01::
The body of California regulations most directly governing RCFE operations is generally found in\: {
=Title 22 community care licensing regulations
~Federal tax code
~Local zoning ordinances only
~Vehicle code
#### RCFEs are licensed under California community care licensing regulations (Title 22). Confirm exact citations with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q02::
This RCFE continuing-education refresher is intended for administrators who are\: {
~Seeking initial certification
=Renewing/maintaining their administrator certificate through continuing education
~Applying for a nursing license
~Becoming physicians
#### The course is a renewal-level CE refresher, not initial certification.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q03::
An RCFE administrator's policies and procedures should be\: {
~Kept secret from staff
=Written, current, accessible to staff, and consistent with applicable regulations
~Optional
~Created only after a citation
#### Current, accessible, regulation-aligned policies support compliant operations.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q04::
RCFE administrators are responsible for ensuring the facility operates in compliance with applicable licensing regulations. {T
#### The administrator is accountable for regulatory compliance.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q05::
When a regulation and a facility's internal preference conflict, the administrator should\: {
~Follow the internal preference
=Follow the applicable regulation and update internal practice
~Ignore both
~Ask residents to decide
#### Applicable regulations take precedence over internal preferences.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q06::
A licensing analyst arrives for an inspection. The administrator should\: {
~Refuse entry
=Cooperate, provide access to required records, and respond professionally
~Hide records
~Send the analyst away
#### Administrators cooperate with authorized licensing inspections and provide required access.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q07::
Procedural standards for documentation in an RCFE primarily exist to\: {
~Create unnecessary paperwork
=Demonstrate compliance, support resident safety, and provide an audit-ready record
~Replace staff training
~Increase fees
#### Documentation standards support compliance, safety, and audit readiness.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q08::
Scenario\: An administrator discovers a facility practice that does not meet a current regulatory standard. The best response is to\: {
~Continue the practice to avoid disruption
=Correct the practice, update policy, document the corrective action, and train staff
~Hide it from staff
~Wait for a citation
#### Proactive correction, documentation, and staff training reflect sound compliance management.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q09::
Posting of the facility license and required notices is generally\: {
~Optional
=Required and should be visible/accessible as specified by regulation
~Only for new facilities
~Prohibited
#### Required postings must be displayed per regulation. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q10::
Staying current with regulatory updates is important for an administrator because\: {
~Regulations never change
=Requirements can change, and compliance must reflect current rules
~It is only the staff's job
~Updates do not affect the facility
#### Regulations evolve; administrators must keep current to remain compliant.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q11::
Which are administrator responsibilities under licensing standards? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Maintaining required records
~%33.33333%Ensuring staff meet training requirements
~%-100.0%Falsifying documents to pass inspection
~%33.33333%Protecting resident rights and safety
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q12::
Which best describes 'procedural standards'? {
~Informal preferences
=Defined, consistent steps for carrying out required processes
~Optional suggestions
~Marketing materials
#### Procedural standards define consistent steps for required processes.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q13::
Maintaining required records for the retention period specified by regulation is part of regulatory compliance. {T
#### Record retention per regulation is a compliance requirement. Confirm retention periods with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q14::
When the administrator is unsure how a specific regulation applies, the most defensible action is to\: {
~Guess and proceed
=Consult the regulation text and seek qualified guidance (e.g., licensing/legal) before acting
~Ignore the question
~Ask a resident
#### Consulting the source and qualified guidance supports compliant, defensible decisions.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-001-Q15::
The overall purpose of this laws-and-regulations refresher is to\: {
~Certify new administrators
=Reinforce current knowledge of the legal and procedural framework that governs RCFE operations
~Replace licensing inspections
~Provide medical training
#### It reinforces current knowledge of the governing framework at a renewal level.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-002

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q01::
Person-centered dementia care is best described as care that\: {
~Treats all residents with dementia the same
=Focuses on the individual's history, preferences, abilities, and dignity
~Prioritizes facility routines over the person
~Avoids family involvement
#### Person-centered dementia care individualizes support around the person's identity, preferences, and abilities.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q02::
Alzheimer's disease is best characterized as\: {
~A normal part of aging
=A progressive neurodegenerative condition affecting memory and cognition
~A temporary, fully reversible condition
~A contagious infection
#### Alzheimer's is a progressive neurodegenerative disease; it is not normal aging. Confirm clinical phrasing with SME.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q03::
Behavioral expressions in dementia (such as agitation) are best understood as\: {
~Deliberate misbehavior
=Often a form of communication of an unmet need or discomfort
~Always requiring medication
~Reasons to isolate the resident
#### Behaviors often communicate unmet needs; identifying triggers is key to person-centered responses.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q04::
Validating a resident's feelings and using a calm approach can help reduce dementia-related distress. {T
#### Validation and calm communication are core person-centered techniques.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q05::
Which communication approach is most appropriate for a resident with moderate dementia? {
~Long, complex explanations
=Short, simple sentences, one step at a time, with patience
~Speaking rapidly
~Correcting every inaccuracy firmly
#### Simple, stepwise, patient communication supports comprehension and reduces distress.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q06::
A meaningful activity program for residents with dementia should be\: {
~Identical for everyone
=Tailored to individual abilities, interests, and life history
~Eliminated to reduce risk
~Limited to passive television
#### Individualized, meaningful activity supports engagement and well-being.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident with dementia becomes upset during the evening and repeatedly asks to 'go home.' A person-centered response is to\: {
~Tell them repeatedly they live here now
=Respond calmly, acknowledge the feeling, offer reassurance and redirection, and look for unmet needs (hunger, fatigue, pain)
~Leave the resident alone until they stop
~Restrict them to their room
#### Acknowledge feelings, reassure, redirect, and assess for unmet needs (including possible 'sundowning' patterns).
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q08::
Which approaches support person-centered dementia care? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Knowing the resident's life story
~%33.33333%Maintaining familiar routines
~%-100.0%Using restraints for convenience
~%33.33333%Involving family in care preferences
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q09::
Staff training on dementia in an RCFE should emphasize\: {
~Speed of task completion only
=Understanding the disease, communication skills, and behavioral support strategies
~Avoiding residents with dementia
~Medication administration by all staff
#### Dementia training emphasizes understanding, communication, and behavioral support.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q10::
Which environmental feature can support residents with dementia? {
~Cluttered, noisy spaces
=Calm, predictable spaces with helpful cues and reduced overstimulation
~Frequently rearranged furniture
~Dim, confusing hallways
#### Calm, cue-rich, low-overstimulation environments support orientation and comfort.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q11::
Preserving dignity for a resident with dementia during personal care includes\: {
~Performing care without explanation
=Explaining steps simply, ensuring privacy, and offering choices when possible
~Rushing to finish
~Discussing the resident in front of others
#### Simple explanation, privacy, and choice preserve dignity.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q12::
Family members can be valuable partners in understanding a resident's preferences and history. {T
#### Families provide insight into the resident's identity and preferences.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q13::
A non-pharmacological first response to mild dementia-related agitation is generally to\: {
~Immediately request sedating medication
=Identify and address triggers, reassure, and redirect
~Isolate the resident
~Ignore the behavior
#### Non-pharmacological, trigger-focused responses are generally first-line; medication decisions are clinical. Confirm clinical guidance with SME.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q14::
Why is consistency of caregivers helpful for residents with dementia? {
~It is not helpful
=Familiar caregivers build trust and reduce confusion and anxiety
~It reduces staffing costs only
~It allows skipping documentation
#### Consistent, familiar caregivers support trust and reduce distress.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-002-Q15::
The overall aim of person-centered dementia foundations is to\: {
~Standardize all residents into one routine
=Support each resident's dignity, abilities, and quality of life
~Reduce family contact
~Increase use of restraints
#### The aim is dignity, ability support, and quality of life for each individual.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-003

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q01::
A primary safety concern for residents with dementia who wander is\: {
~Improved exercise only
=Elopement (leaving the facility unsafely) and related injury risk
~Better sleep
~Reduced supervision needs
#### Wandering raises elopement and injury risk, requiring environmental and care planning.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q02::
A dementia-supportive physical environment generally includes\: {
~Confusing layouts and clutter
=Secure but non-institutional design, clear cues, good lighting, and reduced hazards
~Locked rooms used as punishment
~Removal of all personal items
#### Safe, cue-rich, well-lit, hazard-reduced environments support residents with dementia.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q03::
Documentation related to a resident with dementia should\: {
~Be vague to save time
=Objectively record behaviors, interventions tried, and outcomes to inform care planning
~Include staff opinions and labels
~Be skipped if the resident cannot read it
#### Objective documentation of behaviors and interventions supports individualized care and accountability.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q04::
Restraints (physical or chemical) should not be used for staff convenience or discipline in dementia care. {T
#### Restraints for convenience/discipline are prohibited; least-restrictive, person-centered approaches are required. Confirm regulatory specifics with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q05::
Fall risk is often elevated in residents with dementia because of\: {
~Improved balance
=Impaired judgment, gait/perception changes, and possible medication effects
~Increased strength
~No relevant factors
#### Cognitive, perceptual, gait, and medication factors raise fall risk, requiring prevention measures.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q06::
An effective approach to reduce dementia-related agitation in the environment is to\: {
~Increase noise and activity at all times
=Reduce overstimulation, maintain routine, and provide calm spaces
~Frequently change the resident's room
~Remove orienting cues
#### Calm, predictable, low-stimulation environments reduce agitation.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident with dementia is found near an exit door appearing intent on leaving. The most appropriate response is to\: {
~Physically block and scold the resident
=Calmly approach, reassure, redirect to a safe activity, and document/report to update the safety plan
~Allow them to leave the building
~Lock them in their room
#### Calm redirection plus documentation and safety-plan updates address elopement risk without improper restraint.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q08::
Which measures help keep residents with dementia safe? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Wandering/elopement safety planning
~%33.33333%Hazard reduction and good lighting
~%-100.0%Using seclusion as punishment
~%33.33333%Individualized fall-prevention measures
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q09::
Secured perimeters or alarmed exits in a dementia setting are intended to\: {
~Punish residents
=Support resident safety while maintaining dignity and least-restrictive practices
~Replace supervision entirely
~Restrict resident rights arbitrarily
#### Safety features support protection while preserving dignity; they do not replace supervision. Confirm regulatory specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q10::
When a dementia-related behavior changes suddenly, staff should consider\: {
~That it is always intentional
=A possible underlying medical cause (pain, infection, medication) and report for assessment
~Ignoring it
~Immediate discharge
#### Sudden behavior change may signal a medical issue and should be reported for assessment.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q11::
Care plans for residents with dementia should be\: {
~Static and never updated
=Individualized and updated as needs and behaviors change
~Identical for all residents
~Kept hidden from care staff
#### Care plans should be individualized and updated to remain relevant.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q12::
Clear documentation of dementia-related incidents supports both resident safety and regulatory accountability. {T
#### Incident documentation supports safety and accountability.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q13::
Adequate lighting and contrast in dementia environments help to\: {
~Increase falls
=Reduce confusion, misperception, and fall risk
~Create glare hazards intentionally
~Hide hazards
#### Good lighting/contrast reduce misperception and falls.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q14::
A least-restrictive approach to dementia safety means\: {
~Using the most restrictive option first
=Choosing the option that protects safety while preserving the most freedom and dignity
~Avoiding all safety measures
~Restraining all residents
#### Least-restrictive means balancing safety with freedom and dignity.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-003-Q15::
The overall focus of this course (dementia safety, environment, and documentation) is to\: {
~Provide medication certification
=Strengthen safe environments, risk management, and accurate documentation for residents with dementia
~Eliminate care planning
~Replace family involvement
#### The focus is safe environments, risk management, and documentation.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-004

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q01::
Residents in an RCFE have the right to\: {
=Be treated with dignity, respect, and freedom from abuse
~Be excluded from decisions about their care
~Have personal mail opened by staff routinely
~Be restrained for convenience
#### Resident rights include dignity, respect, and freedom from abuse and mistreatment.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q02::
A resident council primarily exists to\: {
~Manage facility finances
=Give residents a voice in facility matters affecting them
~Replace the administrator
~Discipline residents
#### Resident councils provide a collective voice for residents.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q03::
Preserving resident dignity during personal care includes\: {
=Providing privacy and respectful communication
~Discussing the resident loudly in common areas
~Rushing without explanation
~Ignoring preferences
#### Privacy and respect preserve dignity.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q04::
Residents generally have the right to participate in decisions about their own care and daily life. {T
#### Self-determination and participation are core resident rights.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q05::
Which is an example of protecting a resident's right to privacy? {
~Sharing care details with unauthorized visitors
=Knocking before entering and keeping records confidential
~Posting resident information publicly
~Discussing residents on social media
#### Privacy includes confidentiality and respectful entry practices.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q06::
Abuse prevention in an RCFE is supported primarily by\: {
~Avoiding staff training
=Staff screening, training, supervision, and a clear reporting culture
~Discouraging residents from speaking up
~Ignoring complaints
#### Screening, training, supervision, and reporting culture prevent abuse.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident reports that a staff member spoke to them harshly and ignored their requests. The administrator should\: {
~Dismiss the complaint
=Take the complaint seriously, investigate per policy, protect the resident, and document/report as required
~Tell the resident to stop complaining
~Punish the resident
#### Complaints must be taken seriously, investigated, and addressed with resident protection and documentation. Confirm reporting obligations with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q08::
Which are recognized resident rights? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Right to dignity and respect
~%33.33333%Right to voice grievances without retaliation
~%-100.0%Right to be restrained for convenience
~%33.33333%Right to participate in care decisions
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q09::
Retaliation against a resident for filing a grievance is\: {
~Acceptable
=Prohibited; residents may voice concerns without fear of retaliation
~Encouraged
~Required
#### Retaliation for grievances is prohibited.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q10::
Cultural competency in resident rights means\: {
~Ignoring cultural differences
=Respecting diverse backgrounds, identities, and preferences in care
~Treating everyone identically
~Excluding certain residents
#### Cultural competency respects diversity, including identity and preferences.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q11::
A resident's personal funds or property, when managed by the facility, must be\: {
~Used by staff as needed
=Handled with accountability, accurate records, and protection from misuse
~Mixed with facility funds
~Ignored
#### Resident funds/property require accountability and protection from exploitation. Confirm specific safeguards with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q12::
Residents generally have the right to receive visitors and communicate privately, subject to reasonable safety policies. {T
#### Visitation and private communication are rights, balanced with reasonable safety. Confirm current policy with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q13::
The role of the Long-Term Care Ombudsman generally includes\: {
~Operating the facility
=Advocating for residents and helping resolve concerns/complaints
~Hiring staff
~Setting facility fees
#### The Ombudsman advocates for residents and assists with complaint resolution. Confirm role specifics with SME.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q14::
Protecting dignity during group activities includes\: {
~Forcing participation
=Offering choices and respecting a resident's decision to participate or not
~Excluding shy residents
~Mocking residents who decline
#### Choice and respect for participation decisions preserve dignity.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-004-Q15::
The overall purpose of this course is to\: {
~Certify medication aides
=Reinforce resident rights, dignity, council participation, and abuse prevention
~Replace licensing
~Provide clinical nursing training
#### The purpose is reinforcing rights, dignity, councils, and abuse prevention.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-005

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q01::
In an RCFE, 'assistance with self-administration' of medication generally means staff may\: {
~Make clinical dosing decisions
=Help a resident take their own medication (e.g., reminders, opening containers) within regulatory limits
~Prescribe medications
~Diagnose conditions
#### RCFE staff assist with self-administration within regulatory limits; they do not prescribe or make clinical decisions. Confirm exact scope with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q02::
Centrally stored medications in an RCFE should be\: {
~Left accessible to all residents
=Stored securely, properly labeled, and accounted for per regulation
~Mixed together in one container
~Discarded in regular trash
#### Secure storage, proper labeling, and accountability are required. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q03::
Accurate medication records (such as a medication administration/assistance record) are important because they\: {
~Are optional
=Document what was given/assisted, support safety, and provide an audit trail
~Replace the pharmacy
~Are only for billing
#### Accurate records support safety and provide an audit trail.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q04::
An RCFE administrator's oversight of medication processes does not authorize unlicensed staff to perform tasks reserved for licensed professionals. {T
#### Oversight does not expand scope; licensed tasks remain with licensed professionals. Confirm scope with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q05::
If a medication error or discrepancy is discovered, the appropriate response is to\: {
~Hide it
=Follow facility policy\: ensure resident safety, notify the appropriate licensed/health professional, and document/report
~Blame the resident
~Ignore it if minor
#### Errors require safety-first response, notification, and documentation per policy.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q06::
Proper labeling of a resident's medication generally includes\: {
~No identifying information
=Resident name, medication, dose/directions, and other required pharmacy label elements
~Only the color of the pill
~A staff nickname
#### Proper labels include resident, medication, and directions per pharmacy/regulatory standards.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident who self-administers medications appears increasingly confused and is making errors with their pills. The administrator should\: {
~Take over prescribing
=Report the change to the resident's physician/appropriate professional, review the needs/services plan, and adjust support within regulation
~Ignore it
~Stop all the resident's medications
#### A change in ability triggers reassessment, professional notification, and plan adjustment within regulatory limits.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q08::
Which support safe medication processes in an RCFE? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Secure storage
~%33.33333%Accurate records
~%-100.0%Allowing unlicensed staff to make dosing decisions
~%33.33333%Staff training appropriate to their role
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q09::
Psychotropic medications in older adults require particular attention because they\: {
~Have no side effects
=Can carry significant risks and should be used appropriately with monitoring and oversight
~Should be used for staff convenience
~Replace person-centered care
#### Psychotropics carry risks and require appropriate use, monitoring, and oversight; not for convenience. Confirm clinical/regulatory guidance with SME.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q10::
Disposal of medications should follow\: {
~Whatever is fastest
=Facility policy and applicable regulations for safe, documented disposal
~Flushing everything routinely
~Giving leftovers to other residents
#### Disposal follows policy and regulation; sharing medications between residents is prohibited.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q11::
Medications prescribed for one resident must never be given to another resident. {T
#### Medications are resident-specific and must not be shared.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q12::
Staff who assist with medications should be trained to\: {
~Diagnose new conditions
=Follow proper procedures, recognize and report concerns, and stay within their role
~Adjust doses independently
~Skip documentation
#### Training emphasizes correct procedures, reporting, and staying within role.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q13::
A resident's right to refuse medication generally means staff should\: {
~Force the medication
=Respect the refusal, document it, and notify the appropriate professional
~Hide the refusal
~Discharge the resident immediately
#### Refusals are respected, documented, and reported for follow-up. Confirm process with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q14::
Coordination with the pharmacy and prescribing professional helps ensure\: {
~Confusion
=Correct, current medication information and safe processes
~Higher costs only
~Less accountability
#### Coordination supports accurate, current information and safety.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-005-Q15::
This course addresses medication management at the level of\: {
~Certifying nurses to administer IV medications
=Administrator oversight and safe RCFE medication processes (not medication-administration certification)
~Prescribing authority
~Pharmacy licensure
#### The course covers oversight and safe processes, not administration certification or prescribing.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-006

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q01::
A pre-admission appraisal of a prospective resident is used to\: {
~Set the facility's marketing budget
=Determine whether the facility can meet the person's needs before admission
~Replace the physician's report
~Avoid documentation
#### The appraisal determines whether the facility can meet the prospective resident's needs.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q02::
A needs and services plan should\: {
~Be generic for all residents
=Be individualized, based on assessment, and updated as needs change
~Never be updated
~Be hidden from staff
#### Needs and services plans are individualized and updated with reappraisal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q03::
Reappraisal of a resident is generally triggered by\: {
~Nothing ever
=A significant change in the resident's condition or needs (and per required intervals)
~Only at discharge
~Staff preference
#### Reappraisal occurs with significant changes and at required intervals. Confirm intervals with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q04::
A facility should not admit or retain a resident whose needs it cannot safely meet. {T
#### Admission/retention must align with the facility's ability to meet needs safely. Confirm specific retention criteria with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q05::
Documentation supporting admission generally includes\: {
~No records
=A physician's report/health assessment and required admission documents
~Only a verbal agreement
~Marketing brochures
#### Admission requires a health assessment/physician report and required documents. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q06::
When a resident's needs increase beyond the facility's capacity, the administrator should\: {
~Ignore the change
=Reassess, attempt appropriate accommodations within regulation, and plan a safe transition if needs cannot be met
~Immediately evict without process
~Reduce documentation
#### Reassessment and, if needed, a safe, lawful transition protect the resident. Confirm process with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident's mobility declines and they now need more assistance than the current plan reflects. The administrator should\: {
~Keep the old plan unchanged
=Initiate reappraisal, update the needs and services plan, involve the resident/family and appropriate professionals, and document
~Discharge immediately
~Tell staff to manage informally
#### A change in needs prompts reappraisal, plan update, involvement of the resident/family, and documentation.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q08::
Which belong in a needs and services plan process? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Assessment of the resident's needs
~%33.33333%Resident/family involvement
~%33.33333%Updates upon significant change
~%-100.0%Ignoring the resident's preferences
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q09::
Involving the resident (and family/representative as appropriate) in care planning supports\: {
~Reduced transparency
=Person-centered, individualized, and defensible care decisions
~Less accountability
~Generic care
#### Involvement supports person-centered, individualized, defensible planning.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q10::
Retention decisions should be based primarily on\: {
~The resident's ability to pay only
=Whether the facility can safely and lawfully meet the resident's assessed needs
~Staff convenience
~How long the resident has stayed
#### Retention hinges on the facility's ability to safely and lawfully meet needs.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q11::
The needs and services plan should be accessible to staff who provide the resident's care. {T
#### Care staff need access to the plan to deliver appropriate care.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q12::
A complete admission process helps the facility\: {
~Skip assessment
=Confirm it can meet needs, set expectations, and establish a documented baseline
~Avoid resident input
~Reduce safety
#### A complete admission process confirms fit, sets expectations, and documents a baseline.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q13::
If required admission documentation is incomplete, the administrator should\: {
~Proceed and never follow up
=Obtain the required documentation to complete the record per regulation
~Discard the file
~Create false records
#### Missing documentation must be obtained to complete the compliant record; never falsified.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q14::
Reappraisal documentation should capture\: {
~Only the date
=The changed needs, updated services, and who was involved
~Nothing relevant
~Staff opinions only
#### Reappraisal records should capture changes, updated services, and involvement.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-006-Q15::
The overall purpose of this course is to\: {
~Provide medication certification
=Strengthen admission, retention, reappraisal, and needs-and-services planning practices
~Replace licensing inspections
~Eliminate documentation
#### The purpose is sound admission, retention, reappraisal, and planning practices.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-007

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q01::
An RCFE emergency/disaster plan should\: {
~Exist only on paper and never be practiced
=Be written, current, communicated to staff, and practiced through drills
~Be secret from staff
~Apply only to fires
#### Effective emergency plans are current, communicated, and practiced via drills.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q02::
Emergency drills in an RCFE are important because they\: {
~Waste time
=Help staff and residents respond effectively and reveal gaps to fix
~Are only for new staff
~Replace the written plan
#### Drills build readiness and reveal gaps to correct.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q03::
Maintaining clear, unobstructed exits and pathways primarily supports\: {
~Decoration
=Safe evacuation and fall prevention
~Higher occupancy
~Storage space
#### Clear exits/pathways support safe evacuation and reduce falls.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q04::
Staff should know their roles and responsibilities during different types of emergencies. {T
#### Defined roles support a coordinated emergency response.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q05::
Emergency supplies (water, food, first aid, etc.) should be\: {
~Unnecessary
=Maintained adequately and checked/replenished as needed
~Stored where no one can reach them
~Shared with neighbors routinely
#### Adequate, maintained emergency supplies support continuity during emergencies.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q06::
When considering residents with mobility or cognitive impairments in an evacuation, the plan should\: {
~Treat all residents identically
=Account for individual needs and assistance requirements
~Exclude them
~Assume they will self-evacuate
#### Plans must account for residents needing assistance during evacuation.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q07::
Scenario\: A power outage occurs during extreme heat. The administrator should\: {
~Wait and do nothing
=Activate the emergency plan, ensure resident safety and temperature/medical needs, communicate, and document actions
~Send all staff home
~Ignore residents needing cooling or refrigerated medications
#### Activate the plan, protect residents (heat/medication needs), communicate, and document.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q08::
Which are part of physical-environment safety in an RCFE? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Functioning smoke detectors/alarms
~%33.33333%Clear, unobstructed exits
~%-100.0%Blocked fire exits
~%33.33333%Safe water temperature and hazard control
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q09::
Documentation of emergency drills should include\: {
~Nothing
=Date, type of drill, participants, and any issues/corrective actions
~Only the weather
~Staff opinions about lunch
#### Drill records should capture date, type, participation, and corrective actions.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q10::
Routine inspection/maintenance of safety equipment helps to\: {
~Increase risk
=Ensure equipment works when needed and reduce hazards
~Save documentation time
~Replace drills
#### Maintenance ensures safety equipment functions and reduces hazards.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q11::
Knowing how and when to shut off utilities (e.g., gas, water) can be part of emergency preparedness. {T
#### Utility shutoff knowledge supports certain emergency responses.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q12::
After an emergency, the administrator should\: {
~Avoid review
=Review the response, document outcomes, and update the plan to address gaps
~Blame residents
~Discard records
#### Post-event review and plan updates strengthen future readiness.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q13::
Communication during an emergency should include\: {
~No communication
=A plan for notifying staff, residents, families, and authorities as appropriate
~Only social media
~Rumors
#### A communication plan covers staff, residents, families, and authorities.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q14::
A safe physical environment supports residents primarily by\: {
~Increasing hazards
=Reducing the risk of injury, supporting mobility, and enabling effective emergency response
~Limiting resident rights
~Cutting staffing
#### A safe environment reduces injury risk and supports emergency response.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-007-Q15::
The overall purpose of this course is to\: {
~Provide nursing certification
=Strengthen emergency preparedness and physical-environment safety/controls in the RCFE
~Replace licensing
~Eliminate drills
#### The purpose is emergency preparedness and environmental safety.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-008

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q01::
Effective staff supervision in an RCFE primarily aims to\: {
~Micromanage every action
=Ensure staff perform competently, safely, and consistently with policy and regulation
~Reduce resident care
~Avoid documentation
#### Supervision ensures competent, safe, policy-aligned performance.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q02::
Staff training records should be\: {
~Optional
=Maintained, accurate, and demonstrate required training was completed
~Discarded after hiring
~Kept off-site only
#### Accurate training records demonstrate compliance with training requirements.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q03::
Administrator accountability means the administrator is responsible for\: {
~Only marketing
=Overall facility operations, compliance, staff oversight, and resident well-being
~Nothing once staff are hired
~Only finances
#### The administrator is accountable for operations, compliance, oversight, and resident well-being.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q04::
New staff should receive orientation and required training before or promptly upon assuming their duties, per regulation. {T
#### Orientation/training requirements protect residents; confirm exact timelines with SME/legal.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q05::
Ongoing (continuing) staff training is important because it\: {
~Is never required
=Maintains competency and keeps staff current with practices and regulations
~Only benefits the administrator
~Replaces supervision
#### Continuing training maintains competency and currency.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q06::
When a staff member performs a task incorrectly, an accountable supervisory response is to\: {
~Ignore it
=Provide corrective feedback/retraining, document it, and monitor improvement
~Publicly humiliate the staff member
~Immediately terminate without process
#### Corrective feedback, retraining, documentation, and monitoring are constructive and defensible.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q07::
Scenario\: A licensing review finds gaps in staff training documentation. The administrator should\: {
~Falsify records to fill gaps
=Identify the gaps, complete/verify required training, accurately document it, and implement a tracking system to prevent recurrence
~Blame staff and do nothing
~Hide the records
#### Honest correction, completion of training, accurate documentation, and a tracking system are correct; falsification is prohibited.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q08::
Which are administrator responsibilities for staff management? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Ensuring required training is completed
~%33.33333%Maintaining accurate personnel/training records
~%-100.0%Allowing untrained staff to perform tasks beyond their preparation
~%33.33333%Supervising and supporting staff performance
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q09::
Adequate staffing levels are important because they\: {
~Are irrelevant to care
=Support resident safety, needs, and quality of care
~Only affect costs
~Reduce accountability
#### Adequate staffing supports safety and quality of care.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q10::
Background screening/clearance requirements for staff exist to\: {
~Slow hiring for no reason
=Protect residents from individuals who may pose a risk
~Increase paperwork only
~Replace training
#### Screening helps protect residents; confirm specific clearance requirements with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q11::
An administrator can delegate tasks but remains accountable for the facility's compliance and operations. {T
#### Delegation does not remove the administrator's overall accountability.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q12::
Clear job descriptions and expectations help staff to\: {
~Be confused
=Understand their roles, responsibilities, and limits
~Avoid accountability
~Skip training
#### Clear roles support performance and accountability.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q13::
A supportive supervision approach includes\: {
~Only criticism
=Clear expectations, training, feedback, and recognition
~No communication
~Inconsistent rules
#### Effective supervision blends expectations, training, feedback, and recognition.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q14::
Tracking training due dates and renewals helps the administrator to\: {
~Miss requirements
=Stay compliant and ensure staff competencies are current
~Avoid documentation
~Reduce safety
#### Tracking supports timely compliance and current competencies.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-008-Q15::
The overall purpose of this course is to\: {
~Provide clinical certification
=Strengthen staff supervision, training-record management, and administrator accountability
~Replace licensing
~Eliminate staffing
#### The purpose is supervision, training records, and accountability.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/RCFE/RCFE-CETP-009

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q01
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q01::
Accurate business records in an RCFE support\: {
~Concealment of operations
=Compliance, financial accountability, and audit readiness
~Higher fees only
~Avoiding inspections
#### Accurate records support compliance, accountability, and audit readiness.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q02
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q02::
Records that must be retained should be kept\: {
~As briefly as convenient
=For the period and in the manner required by applicable regulation
~Only until the next month
~Never
#### Retention follows regulatory requirements; confirm retention periods with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q03
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q03::
'Claim-safe' communication in operations generally means\: {
~Making unverified promises
=Communicating accurately and avoiding misleading or unsupported claims
~Exaggerating services
~Hiding information from residents
#### Claim-safe communication is accurate and avoids misleading or unsupported statements.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q04
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q04::
Marketing and admission materials should accurately represent the services the facility actually provides. {T
#### Accurate representation avoids misleading prospective residents.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q05
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q05::
Resident financial records handled by the facility must be\: {
~Combined with facility funds
=Kept accurate, separate as required, and protected from misuse
~Shared publicly
~Estimated
#### Resident funds require accuracy, required separation, and protection. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q06
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q06::
Confidentiality of resident and business information requires that information is\: {
~Shared freely
=Disclosed only to authorized parties and protected from improper access
~Posted online
~Discussed publicly
#### Confidential information is protected and shared only with authorized parties.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q07
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q07::
Scenario\: A prospective resident's family asks whether the facility provides a level of skilled care it does not actually offer. The administrator should\: {
~Imply the facility offers it to secure the admission
=Accurately describe the services the facility provides and not make unsupported claims
~Avoid answering
~Promise to add the service without basis
#### Accurate, claim-safe communication prevents misrepresentation and protects residents.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q08
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q08::
Which support sound RCFE business operations? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Accurate financial and operational records
~%33.33333%Proper retention of required records
~%-100.0%Misleading marketing claims
~%33.33333%Confidential handling of sensitive information
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q09
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q09::
When required records are requested during an inspection, the administrator should\: {
~Refuse
=Provide the required records in an organized, accurate, and timely manner
~Provide falsified records
~Delay indefinitely
#### Required records should be provided accurately and timely; falsification is prohibited.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q10
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q10::
A clear, written admission agreement helps to\: {
~Confuse residents
=Set transparent expectations about services, fees, and terms
~Hide fees
~Avoid accountability
#### A clear admission agreement sets transparent expectations.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q11
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q11::
Backups and protection of important records help prevent loss of required documentation. {T
#### Record protection/backups guard against loss of required documentation.}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q12
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q12::
Fee changes or billing practices should be\: {
~Hidden from residents
=Communicated transparently and consistent with the agreement and regulation
~Applied without notice
~Inconsistent
#### Fees should be transparent and consistent with the agreement and regulation. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q13
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q13::
Honest, accurate communication with residents and families builds\: {
~Distrust
=Trust and supports a defensible operation
~Liability only
~Confusion
#### Honest communication builds trust and supports defensibility.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q14
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q14::
Organized recordkeeping systems help the administrator to\: {
~Lose documents
=Locate, maintain, and produce required records efficiently
~Avoid compliance
~Reduce transparency
#### Organized systems support efficient, compliant recordkeeping.
}

// question: RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q15
::RCFE-RCFE-CETP-009-Q15::
The overall purpose of this course is to\: {
~Provide clinical certification
=Strengthen business operations, recordkeeping, and claim-safe communications in the RCFE
~Replace licensing
~Eliminate records
#### The purpose is sound operations, recordkeeping, and claim-safe communication.
}

